April 18 (film)Events* 796 ;ndash; King Æthelred I of Northumbria is murdered in Corbridge by a group led by his ealdormen, Ealdred and Wada. The ''patrician'' Osbald is placed on the throne, but is within 27 days abdicated.*1025 ;ndash; Bolesław I Chrobry|Bolesław Chrobry is crowned in Gniezno, becoming the first King of Poland.*1506 ;ndash; The cornerstone of the current St. Peter's Basilica is laid.*1518 ;ndash; Bona Sforza is crowned as queen consort of Poland.*1521 ;ndash; Trial of Martin Luther begins its second day during the assembly of the Diet of Worms. He refuses to recant his teachings despite the risk of excommunication.*1689 ;ndash; Bostonians rise up in rebellion against Sir Edmund Andros.*1738 ;ndash; ''Real Academia de la Historia'' ("Royal Academy of History") is founded in Madrid.*1775 ;ndash; American Revolution: The British advancement by sea begins; Paul Revere and other riders warn the countryside of the troop movements.*1797 ;ndash; The Battle of Neuwied: French victory against the Austrians.*1807 ;ndash; The Harwich ferry disaster occurred near the North Sea port of Harwich on the Essex coast (England) in which 60-90 people drowned during the capsizing of a small ferry boat.*1831 ;ndash; The University of Alabama is founded.*1848 ;ndash; American victory at the battle of Cerro Gordo opens the way for invasion of Mexico.*1857 ;ndash; "The Spirits Book" by Allan Kardec is published, marking the birth of Spiritualism in France.*1864 ;ndash; Battle of Dybbøl: A Prussian-Austrian army defeats Denmark and gains control of Schleswig. Denmark surrenders the province in the following peace settlement.*1880 ;ndash; An F4 tornado strikes Marshfield, Missouri, killing 99 people and injuring 100.*1897 ;ndash; The Greco-Turkish War is declared between Greece and the Ottoman Empire.*1899 ;ndash; The St. Andrew's Ambulance Association is granted a Royal Charter by Queen Victoria.*1902 ;ndash; Quetzaltenango, the second largest city of Guatemala, is destroyed by an earthquake.*1906 ;ndash; An earthquake and fire destroy much of San Francisco, California.*1909 ;ndash; Joan of Arc is beatified in Rome.*1912 ;ndash; The Cunard liner  brings 705 survivors from the  to New York City.*1915 ;ndash; French pilot Roland Garros is shot down and glides to a landing on the German side of the lines during World War I.*1923 ;ndash; Yankee Stadium, "The House that Ruth Built", opens.*1924 ;ndash; Simon ; Schuster publishes the first crossword puzzle book.*1930 ;ndash; BBC reported there was no news, then played out with piano music.*1936 ;ndash; The first Champions Day is celebrated in Detroit, Michigan.*1942 ;ndash; World War II: The Doolittle Raid on Japan. Tokyo, Yokohama, Kobe and Nagoya are bombed.*  1942   ;ndash; Pierre Laval becomes Prime Minister of Vichy France.*1943 ;ndash; World War II: Operation Vengeance, Admiral Isoroku Yamamoto is killed when his aircraft is shot down by U.S. fighters over Bougainville Island.*1945 ;ndash; Over 1,000 bombers attack the small island of Heligoland, Germany.*1946 ;ndash; The International Court of Justice holds its inaugural meeting in The Hague, Netherlands.*1949 ;ndash; The keel for the aircraft carrier 6 is laid down at Newport News Drydock and Shipbuilding. However, construction is canceled five days later, resulting in the Revolt of the Admirals.*1954 ;ndash; Gamal Abdel Nasser seizes power in Egypt.*1955 ;ndash; Twenty-nine nations meet at Bandung, Indonesia, for the first Asian-African Conference.*1958 ;ndash; A United States federal court rules that poet Ezra Pound be released from an insane asylum.*1961 ;ndash; The Vienna Convention on Diplomatic Relations, a cornerstone of modern international relations, is adopted.*  1961   ;ndash; CONCP is founded in Casablanca as a united front of African movements opposing Portuguese colonial rule.*1974 ;ndash; The Prime Minister of Pakistan Zulfikar Ali Bhutto inaugurates Lahore's dry port.*1980 ;ndash; The Republic of Zimbabwe (formerly Rhodesia) comes into being, with Canaan Banana as the country's first President. The Zimbabwean dollar replaces the Rhodesian dollar as the official currency.*1981 ;ndash; The longest professional baseball game is begun in Pawtucket, Rhode Island. The game is suspended at 4:00 the next morning and finally completed on June 23.*1983 ;ndash; A suicide bomber destroys the United States embassy in Beirut, Lebanon, killing 63 people.*1988 ;ndash; The United States launches Operation Praying Mantis against Iranian naval forces in the largest naval battle since World War II.*1992 ;ndash; General Abdul Rashid Dostum revolts against President Mohammad Najibullah of the Democratic Republic of Afghanistan and allies with Ahmad Shah Massoud to capture Kabul.*1996 ;ndash; In Lebanon, at least 106 civilians are killed when the Israel Defense Forces shell the United Nations compound at Quana where more than 800 civilians had taken refuge.*2007 ;ndash; The Supreme Court of the United States upholds the Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act in a 5–4 decision.* 2007 ;ndash; A series of bombings, two of them being suicides, occur in Baghdad, killing 198 and injuring 251.*2013 ;ndash; A suicide bombing in a Baghdad cafe kills 27 people and injures another 65.*2014 ;ndash; Sixteen people are killed in an avalanche on Mount Everest.Births*1480 ;ndash; Lucrezia Borgia, Italian daughter of Pope Alexander VI (d. 1519)*1503 ;ndash; Henry II of Navarre, (d. 1555)*1590 ;ndash; Ahmed I, Ottoman sultan (d. 1617)*1605 ;ndash; Giacomo Carissimi, Italian priest and composer (d. 1674)*1648 ;ndash; Jeanne Guyon, French mystic and author (d. 1717)*1666 ;ndash; Jean-Féry Rebel, French violinist and composer (d. 1747)*1740 ;ndash; Sir Francis Baring, 1st Baronet, English banker and politician (d. 1810)*1759 ;ndash; Jacques Widerkehr, French cellist and composer (d. 1823)*1771 ;ndash; Karl Philipp, Prince of Schwarzenberg (d. 1820)*1772 ;ndash; David Ricardo, English economist and politician (d. 1823)*1794 ;ndas